06184nam a22012495i 9780691208701DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912087017 a10.1515/97806912087012doi  a(DE-B1597)566219  a(OCoLC)1197700235  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBJ1521 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a179.92231 aSreenivasan, Gopal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmotion and Virtue /cGopal Sreenivasan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b8 b/w illus., 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Credo -- t2. The Integral View -- tPreliminaries -- t3. Emotion -- t4. Disunity of Virtue -- t5. Character Traits -- tArguments -- t6. Adverbial Requirements -- t7. Salience without a Black Box -- t8. Moral Deference and the Proto-authority of Affect -- t9. Recap with Courage -- tConsequences -- t10. Agents versus Acts -- t11. Against the Priority of Principle -- t12. Should Virtue Be Taught? -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA novel approach to the crucial role emotion plays in virtuous actionWhat must a person be like to possess a virtue in full measure? What sort of psychological constitution does one need to be an exemplar of compassion, say, or of courage? Focusing on these two examples, Emotion and Virtue ingeniously argues that certain emotion traits play an indispensable role in virtue. With exemplars of compassion, for instance, this role is played by a modified sympathy trait, which is central to enabling these exemplars to be reliably correct judges of the compassionate thing to do in various practical situations. Indeed, according to Gopal Sreenivasan, the virtue of compassion is, in a sense, a modified sympathy trait, just as courage is a modified fear trait.While he upholds the traditional definition of virtue as a species of character trait, Sreenivasan discards other traditional precepts. For example, he rejects the unity of the virtues and raises new questions about when virtue should be taught. Unlike orthodox virtue ethics, moreover, his account does not aspire to rival consequentialism and deontology. Instead Sreenivasan repudiates the ambitions of virtue imperialism.Emotion and Virtue makes significant contributions to moral psychology and the theory of virtue alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCompassion. 0aCourage. 0aEmotionsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aEmotions. 0aVirtue. 0aVirtues. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aA Theory of Virtue: Excellence in Being for the Good.  aAlasdair MacIntyre.  aAristotle.  aIntelligent Virtue.  aJohn McDowell.  aJulia Annas.  aJulia Driver.  aOn Virtue Ethics.  aPlato.  aRobert Merrihew Adams.  aRosalind Hursthouse.  aThomas Hurka.  aUneasy Virtue.  aVirtue, Vice, and Value.  acharacter education.  acleverness.  acontinence.  adisunity of virtues.  adisunity position.  aempathy.  aeudaimonism.  aexecutive virtue.  agenerosity.  agood ends.  aindividual virtue.  aintegral view.  amoral deference.  amoral justification.  amoral knowledge.  amoral principles.  aparticularism.  apriority to agents.  apsychology.  arectified sympathy trait.  asituationist critique.  asympathy.  avirtue ethics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert